Do Good. Feel Good. Look Good.🙌🏽🙌🏽🙌🏽

As the year ends, taking some time to reflect…very grateful for all the opportunities I had this past year to share my culture and other cultures through so many beauty segments – and also honoured to share ways that beauty buys can be so much more than skin deep.

We show our support with our spending dollars – wanted to share my last segment for 2022 with you -- features  a few of my fav brands doing amazing things to give back.💋

 

💗Everist - 1% for the Planet promise - Everist donates 1% of all sales to support the sustainable initiatives  -- Beyond that, they make sure shipping materials are 100% recycled and 100% recyclable (basically, paper).  They also vowto clean 1 lb of ocean-bound plastic for every email subscription

💗U Beauty - For every order consumers make, U Beauty donates $1 to One Tree Planted, as part of their ongoing initiative with this non-profit dedicated to reforestation. All products are manufactured in a CO2-free facility, and they keep the lights on with 100% green energy.

💗Rare Beauty – 100% of sales of the Lip Souffle Matte Lip Cream in Limitless go to the Rare Impact Fund to support mental health services for young people.  Overall, across all products 1% of Rare Beauty’s annual sales go directly to the Rare Impact Fund to expand mental health services in underserved communities.

💗CeraVe – In partnership with the Canadian Nurses Foundation they have created a scholarship fund for baccalaureate nursing students identifying within the BIPOC community.   In 2023, they’re increasing their investment to provide even more funds to help promote diversity, equity, and inclusion among Canadian nursing students. 

💗MAC Cosmetics -100% of sales of Viva Glam lipsticks go to the Viva Glam Fund. In Canada those dollars go towards those living with HIV/AIDS, providing security for the LGBTQ+ community and education for Indigenous youth.

There is a long road of work ahead, but taking a moment of reflection today, on a day that I did not think may ever happen, but is here❤️🥺🙌🏽

One week until the big 4️⃣5️⃣…LONG CAPTION COMING YOUR WAY⚠️

I tend to focus on the failures instead of the wins, so taking a moment to remind ME of a few not so little feats:

❤️For over 15 years, I had an incredible career in TV advertising with Corus. I managed my own Entertainment team, working with the biggest movie studios and making movie magic come alive on the small screen – igniting my passion for film and pop culture.📽️

❤️During those same 15 years I had a 2nd career in full swing, as the Editor in Chief of a bridal magazine, and then Founder & EIC of my own fashion & lifestyle mag, Fusia. I loved the print days  and have loved covering BIPOC films at TIFF since

❤️At 39 years old, I left my cushy corporate career with Corus and took a big leap (and even bigger paycut🙈) to pursue my passion for journalism fulltime – writing for CBC, InStyle, Chatelaine, Vogue, VICE, Refinery29, Elle Canada, FASHION as well as weekly culture commentary with Global News. 
I also started working in front of the camera as a Beauty & Culture Expert📺, merging my journalism, beauty and culture editorial background – appearing regularly on national TV.

❤️At 40 years old I created, and became the Executive Producer and Host of a talkshow with Global News Radio called kultur’D📻  4 years later, I started a new radio venture with FLOW 98.7 for a namesake show ‘Real Talk with Meera E.’  This is when I became a full-on multi hyphenate:
🎙️📺📝

❤️Yesterday, I took a first BIG step towards my newest venture, adding a new title to my growing list…this one is going to take time, but will be so worth it🙏🏽  Less than 24 hours later though I said goodbye to one of my favourite gigs🥺

I need to remind myself every so often, that for every small step backwards, every “no thank you” that has come my way, I’ve made so many big steps forward, many “sign on the dotted line"wins despite all the odds.🙌🏽🙌🏽🙌🏽

If you’re feeling like me today,  remind yourself how far you’ve come. The things I would tell 20 year, old, 30 year old, 40 year old…and even a week ago me, I couldn't have imagined.

Be kind to you. 💋

HEART ON THE SLEEVE CAPTION ❤️
In highschool I went to a taping of @marilyndenis  original show at 299 Queen. I remember we got front row seats and were so excited. Being in the CHUM building felt electric – and it literally was✨ (Electric Circus, Speakers Corner, FT…the list goes on)😍.  I had written in my diary from age 11 that I wanted to be a journalist, but being immersed in TV land on that visit, watching Marilyn in her element solidified my love for storytelling on-screen.📺

From my first job out of university at YTV (20+ years ago on a little slime filled show called Uh-Oh🙈), I didn't looked back and found myself in all realms of media since.

Though never did I imagine standing in front of the camera, side by side with Marilyn -- but life is crazy and sometimes very kind. My first two segments with @themarilyndenisshow were over Skype during pandemic – and then we finally got to meet in studio the following year.

Even though it’s only been three years of beauty & culture on MDS for me, I will always be grateful to Marilyn and the entire team for allowing me to share so much of my culture on national television, from our Diwali to Holi segments and everything in between.
💙💚❤️🧡💛💜 

Watching the farewell episodes these past few days  has got me feeling emotional🥺…because Marilyn is special and makes each person she’s speaking with feel that way too💗. From our borough bond, living literally two streets away for so many years, to her kindness and concern when I was sick for several months last year between shingles and seizures, she is one of a kind, with an incredible team of producers like @sushrao @manamansour -- and a slew more with a crew bar none.

I’m so glad I’ll still hear her voice in the mornings on the radio – and hope you savour these last few episodes as you are showered with all the love, Marilyn😘.

Thanks for making me a small part of your beautiful journey and being a big part in mine💕

.

Our skin changes during menopause. Thinning hair is a reality for many as we age.

Let’s talk about it.

This week I did a segment with Your Morning on gift guides for every kind of mom or mom figure in your life.  I wanted to put some extra attention on the older moms & grandmoms.  While we talk about inclusivity of gender, race, sexuality…age is still very much left out of the equation.😕

So, here’s a little extra info on Vichy Neovadiol Skincare and Nioxin Haircare and why they matter to us (and our mommas)🙌🏽🙌🏽🙌🏽

Something we don’t talk about enough is at menopause, hormonal changes have a visible impact on the skin too. Neovadiol reactivates the mechanisms of the skin during menopause thanks to a unique synergy of active ingredients: Proloxylane + Cassia extract. Ready for some pillowtalk?😴

☁️ Your pillowcases might not be on your mind, but they are on your face and body every night. That's why you should give them extra attention by keeping up with routine hygiene practices. ☁️ 

☁️ There are many reasons why changing pillowcases often is hygienic and beneficial for your skin and body. However, most people don't know how often to change them and replace them with clean ones.

‼️ Now…..WHY IS THIS SO IMPORTANT?! 

☁️ Regularly changing out your pillowcase is beneficial for skincare and fighting acne. Along with the oils and bodily excrement that build up on your pillowcases as you sleep, any dirt or makeup that wasn’t removed properly will also get onto the material, clogging your pores and irritating your skin.

☁️ So how often should you change your pillowcase to avoid acne and enhance your skincare journey?

📌 Keep a supply of extra pillowcases for convenience, and try to get on a schedule for changing sheets each week🤯 I'm guilty of not doing this weekly but going to start practicing what I preach💋

I’ve been feeling conflicted over whether I should post for work and client events during this awful time. For example, this morning I had a TV segment and thought it right to share on it – it is part of my livelihood.

Like most other people who need to continue to work and be paid, they must show up for their jobs in offices, hospitals, construction sites, whatever their line of work. 

For those in the public sphere, the content creators and other forms of broadcast media I think its okay to show up too (thanks for that reminder @averyfrancis❤️) .

 I see a lot of people criticized for not speaking up and carrying on with their work, but everyone isn’t comfortable with being vocal. Some people share their support by picking up the phone and checking in on their loved ones, others with private donations and educating themselves.  I feel grateful to be able to get some respite with moments like this with my peers and friends – knowing so many others cannot escape their heartache and suffering.

Its already ugly enough – I hope my friends who may have other perspectives on what is happening in the world know that I still love them, it hasn’t changed in the last week. I hope you too will respect me for my perspectives.

I had a seizure two hours before this interview. Uber was already at the door…and as I was putting my heels on, fell to the ground. This was last November, and I was in a cycle of seizure after seizure every couple of months. I couldn’t seem to hit the three-month seizure free milestone for over two years and my self-esteem and exhaustion was peak.

 When I regained consciousness, lying on the couch my husband had carried me to, I started crying. My husband said, let’s get you upstairs, changed and in bed. But I was adamant and said ‘No, I’m going. Not again. Let me rest half hour and then I’m going downtown. I won’t let this stop me’. Jon was VERY reluctant, but he saw my determination, and as always believed.  I fixed my hair and makeup which had smeared all over my face and called another Uber💜

When I got there, the first person I saw was Sangita. She saw something was off “Are you okay?” I felt the tears welling up. I told her about the seizure…please go home she said while hugging me. But I was SO determined. Head throbbing, body aching, I did it. 

And it was thanks to kindness from the etalk team helping me out with photos and videos because I wasn’t quite coordinated as you can see from my taping Charlie's leg.
I even laughed at the end of the night, talking and listening to Will Wong and Maurie exchange jokes.  I’m sure none of these people remember seeing me this night, but kindness really counts and small gestures can mean all the world.  I love this book, loved the series and so glad I did this. 

Sometimes epilepsy stops us in our tracks. We need the rest and should absolutely take it. That in itself is strength. But sometimes on nights like that one, it also shows us we are resilient…much more than we give ourselves credit for.

Two days later I got on the air and shared the interview.
Two months after this interview I had another seizure in January…but here I am today NINE months seizure-free. I know another one will come and the count will begin again, but for now, for this moment I’ll celebrate.

This has been my go-to Halloween look many a time…I’ve had this ragdoll dress for over 15 years and I just change it up a bit each year😜 The kids always want me to get dressed up with them and of course I oblige! C’mon Halloween is a makeup lover’s dream👻
It can be intimidating for the makeup novice – but seriously you can pull off some super simple looks that look super creepy (or cute) too!🎃

Step 1: Prime the skin and apply foundation and setting powder as per usual. You can go a few shades lighter for that ‘life sucked out of me’ look 😉

Step 2: For this look, the eyes are a big focal point. We are creating two half moons under the low lids. You can use any brand of makeup or even white facepaint for the half moons; I really like how the @nyxcosmetics_canada jumbo pencil works here.

Then we want to really exaggerate the lower lashes by drawing them on with black liquid eyeliner.

Step 3: For the upper lids, you want to go deep with a dark red/grey/black shadow (there are no rules!) and BIG lashes for upper and lower lids -- can use falsies or just go heavy and layer on that mascara. For the lower lids instead of falsies, as above, you can use a waterproof liquid eyeliner, @stilacosmetics is my favourite for this look and it does not budge👌🏽

Step 4: Getting cheeky. We want to add two bright circles on the apples of the cheeks 🍭🍭you can use lipstick/eyeshadow/blush for this) I really like using a cream blush here, currently obsessed with the @shiseido Whipped Powder Blush. Can also stipple on a few dots of black or brown eyeliner for freckles on the nose and cheeks.

Step 5: Shatter the skin. For a SUPER simple stitched skin look, just apply temporary tattoos – you can find them anywhere and only cost a few bucks.  Its also pretty simple to draw the cracks, just use that same liquid liner and make tiny zigzag marks around your face. Remember, we’re not aiming for perfection…you’re supposed to be a mess, so just have fun with it.🥳 You can add some colourful square patches with some vertical black lines and x’s around the edges.

This post was inspired by the article/zine “Give Up Activism” by Andrew X, which was originally written as a response to their observations on the Global Day of Action on June 18th, 1999 in London.

(SLIDE 1 TEXT: We don’t need “activists.”)

(SLIDE 2 TEXT: Our everyday lives require radical change. We all need to reimagine our priorities and routines so that cultures and practices of social justice and collective liberation are naturally acclimated into them. This reimagining includes dismantling the idea of activists as separate and distinct identities.)

(SLIDE 3 TEXT: We need to stop idolizing and romanticizing the idea of the “activist” as it exists in our collective imagination as this noteworthy role, title, or identity that distinguishes us from others, even makes us “better” than others. We all need to collectively participate in the “work” and integrate it into our daily lives so well that stating “I’m an activist” is as obvious as saying “I’m a human.”)

(SLIDE 4 TEXT: We won’t need heroes when we are all liberators who also refuse to oppress. We won’t need saviors when we are all supporting each other from endangerment. We won’t need to be superhumans, simply kind and compassionate ones. We don’t need such a special division of people but a world where such divisions are obsolete. If activism is a deviation from an apathetic, complicit, and indifferent norm, then the norm needs to change.)

Hats off to the little things.💗 Going into 2024 with a deeper  appreciation that the little things are really the big ones.

I spent far too much time last year in self doubt, insecurity and saying yes too many times I really wanted to say no. 
So much energy was spent on people and situations that didn't value me or my worth. 

My parents, my children, my husband, closest friends and family - I want to shower them with kindness, pick up the phone more often, make more time, let them know how much they matter and give them all their flowers now not later. 
🌸🌼🌸

My word this year is KINDNESS. Sound cheesy?!? I don't care. Because it's also kindness to me. 

Our time here is limited. If I left this earth tomorrow, none of the other stuff would matter. How I treated those closest to me would. 

Cheers to all the tiny moments 2024 will bring and the perfectly imperfect canvas it will weave 💗
